Dear Ms.Lin:<br><br>
I had the oportunity to see the memorial a few years ago <br>
while at a Pro-Life rally held in Washington.  I recall <br>
descending the steps, sinking into your creation and <br>
then feeling very depressed.  After watching the PBS/POV <br>
special about the memorial, I am now simply bitter.  <br><br>
I have long believed that if students in our universities <br>
reflect the politically correct tone, as you and your works <br>
obviously do, then special recognition, achievement and <br>
rewards await them from the popular culture.  You are, <br>
in my humble opinion, an example of achievment gained from <br>
striking the right and trendy cultural notes as opposed to <br>
any classically technical or artistic talent. A sleek, black <br>
scar dug into the ground certainly sits well with the <br>
acedemic Left who taught you and who hated our soldiers, <br>
but it does not represent a memorial we can all embrace as <br>
Americans.  <br><br>
You claimed you tried to create a non-political piece for <br>
the soldiers lost in Viet Nam, and yet all of your works<br>
featured in the PBS /POV film seemed more at home<br>
with the Left.  I wonder if you could concoct a simplistic<br>
piece that might memorialize the death of millions of unborn <br>
children? I have a feeling such a memorial may not get you<br>
the &quot;achievement&quot; you gain from your commissioners.<br>

